article.headline: Utes' Smith scores 15 of her 22 in second half
article.linkText: Utah extends home win streak to 22
article.story:
SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- Tall players have trouble guarding Utah's
Kim Smith.

Smaller players apparently have as much difficulty.

The 6-foot-1 sophomore took advantage of San Francisco's
switching defense and scored 15 of her 22 points in the second half
and No. 25 Utah surged past the Dons 75-48 Friday to extend its
home winning streak to 22.

"We have a spread motion offense, and I love to cut to the
basket," Smith said. "Today, we were running our stuff great and
they were losing me. My teammates found me and I just needed to lay
the ball in the basket."

Smith tied her scoring season-high by shooting 10-of-13, mostly
on easy baskets cutting to the hoop, as Utah shot 56 percent from
the field. She also made 2-of-3 3-pointers.

"They switched so much on defense that we got a lot of guard
matchups on Kim and she made most of her points inside," Utah
coach Elaine Elliott said.

As good as the Utah offense was, the players say the game turned
when the Utes' pressure defense was intensified.

"We played really hard on defense and that got our offense
going. We really made them work and just waited for them to make
mistakes," said Carley Marshall, who had 13 points.

Shona Thorburn added 10 as the Utes have won four of their last
five.

Carey Sauer scored 15 points and Mary Jane Krueger had 10 as the
Dons saw the their three-game winning streak stopped. San Francisco
shot just 21 percent in the second half and 32 percent for the game
against Utah's pressure defense.

"We let them get some stuff early, but we changed a few things
and got our defense going. That's what we know. We're a
defensive-minded team and everything else follows," Smith said.

It was the Dons' first road game in almost a month. They have
yet to win on the road this year.

Utah took control midway through the first half as San Francisco
had a hard time finding any easy shots. The Dons' starting outside
players made just 3-of-18 field goals.

Smith sparked an 11-0 run to start the second half with a
3-pointer and capped it with a layup to put Utah ahead 45-22. The
Dons missed their first five shots of the half and nine of their
first 10.

"I asked them to have that killer instinct. We haven't put
teams away enough when they've been down. But we did it tonight,"
Elliott said.

In Utah's last home game, Utah snapped a string of 184 straight
games with a 3 pointer by shooting 0-for-10. Against the Dons, the
Utes found it tough to miss from beyond the arc as they converted
8-of-11 3-point shots.

"We're shooting the ball so much better. We're getting good 3s
and they're coming in the flow of the offense," Elliott said.

The Utes forced 11 first-half turnovers on their way to a 34-22
halftime advantage.

Utah is 4-0 against San Francisco at home.
